---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "The Complete Guide to STI Testing",
  "description": "Understand window periods, testing frequency, and what to expect at a clinic. Your evidence-based guide to STI testing.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "The Nookie Nook"
  },
  "mainEntity": {
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is an STI window period?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The window period is the time between potential exposure to an STI and when a test can accurately detect the infection. Testing too early can result in a false negative."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do all STIs show symptoms?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Many common STIs, such as chlamydia and gonorrhea, are frequently asymptomatic. This is why regular testing is crucial even if you feel completely healthy."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What should I expect during an STI test?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Tests typically involve a urine sample, a blood draw, or swabs from the genital area, throat, or rectum. The process is generally quick and straightforward."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
};
---
<SiteLayout
  site="nookienook"
  title="Complete STI Testing Guide & Window Periods | The Nookie Nook"
  description="Understand window periods, testing frequency, and what to expect at a clinic. Your evidence-based guide to STI testing."
  canonical="https://thenookienook.com/sti-testing-guide"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>The Complete STI Testing Guide</h1>
      <p>Clear facts on window periods, test types, and testing frequency.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <p>Part of our <a href="/sites/nookienook/sexual-health-guide">Comprehensive Sexual Health Guide</a> series.</p>

      <p>Getting tested for Sexually Transmitted Infections (STIs) is a routine part of maintaining your overall health. Despite lingering societal stigma, STI testing is a standard, responsible medical practice. This guide provides evidence-based information on when to get tested, what to expect, and how to interpret the timelines of different infections.</p>

      <h2>When to Get Tested</h2>
      <p>Your testing frequency should align with your sexual activity and risk factors. The CDC provides general guidelines, but your individual needs may vary:</p>
      <div class="card">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>General Baseline:</strong> At least once a year for all sexually active adults.</li>
          <li><strong>Higher Frequency (Every 3-6 Months):</strong> Recommended if you have multiple or anonymous partners, or if you engage in higher-risk activities without barrier methods.</li>
          <li><strong>Event-Based:</strong> Before starting a new sexual relationship, or if a previous partner informs you they have tested positive.</li>
          <li><strong>Symptom-Based:</strong> Immediately if you experience unusual discharge, pain during urination, unexpected bleeding, or genital sores.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Understanding Window Periods</h2>
      <p>A "window period" is the crucial time gap between an exposure to an STI and the point when a test can reliably detect it. Testing too early can result in a false negative. If you've had a potential exposure, you may need a baseline test immediately, followed by a re-test after the window period has passed.</p>

      <div class="timeline-container">
        <h3>STI Window Periods Timeline</h3>
        <p><em>Note: These are general ranges. Always consult a healthcare provider for specific medical advice.</em></p>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-disease">Gonorrhea & Chlamydia</div>
          <div class="timeline-bar-wrapper">
            <div class="timeline-bar" style="width: 20%; left: 0%; background-color: var(--accent-color);"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-time">1 - 2 Weeks</div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-disease">Syphilis</div>
          <div class="timeline-bar-wrapper">
            <div class="timeline-bar" style="width: 40%; left: 10%; background-color: var(--accent-color);"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-time">3 - 6 Weeks</div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-disease">HIV (RNA/4th Gen Test)</div>
          <div class="timeline-bar-wrapper">
            <div class="timeline-bar" style="width: 30%; left: 5%; background-color: var(--accent-color);"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-time">2 - 4 Weeks</div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-disease">HIV (Antibody Test)</div>
          <div class="timeline-bar-wrapper">
            <div class="timeline-bar" style="width: 50%; left: 20%; background-color: var(--accent-color);"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-time">3 - 12 Weeks</div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-disease">Hepatitis B & C</div>
          <div class="timeline-bar-wrapper">
            <div class="timeline-bar" style="width: 60%; left: 30%; background-color: var(--accent-color);"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-time">8 - 12 Weeks (or more)</div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-disease">Herpes (Blood Test)</div>
          <div class="timeline-bar-wrapper">
            <div class="timeline-bar" style="width: 70%; left: 30%; background-color: var(--accent-color);"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-time">12 - 16 Weeks (for antibodies)</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>What to Expect at the Clinic</h2>
      <p>A "full panel" test doesn't always mean the same thing at every clinic. It's important to be specific about what you are being tested for. A standard screening typically involves:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Urine Test:</strong> Commonly used to detect Chlamydia and Gonorrhea.</li>
        <li><strong>Blood Draw:</strong> Used to check for HIV, Syphilis, Hepatitis, and sometimes Herpes (though swab tests are preferred for active Herpes sores).</li>
        <li><strong>Swabs:</strong> Can be taken from the throat, rectum, or genitals to check for localized infections like Chlamydia, Gonorrhea, or HPV.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Reading Your Results</h2>
      <p>Results are usually available within a few days to a week. A <strong>Negative</strong> result means no infection was detected (assuming the window period has passed). A <strong>Positive</strong> result means an infection is present. Remember that many STIs (like Chlamydia, Gonorrhea, and Syphilis) are completely curable with antibiotics. Others (like HIV and Herpes) are highly manageable with antiviral medications.</p>

      <p>If you test positive, it is essential to follow your doctor's treatment plan and inform recent sexual partners so they can also get tested and treated.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <script is:inline>
    // Placeholder for inline JS
  </script>
  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.2rem; }

    .content-section { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
    .content-section h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .content-section p { margin-bottom: 1.2rem; font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.7; }
    .content-section a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: underline; }
    .content-section a:hover { color: var(--text-primary); }

    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    .card ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0; }
    .card li { margin-bottom: 0.8rem; line-height: 1.6; }

    .timeline-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2.5rem 0; }
    .timeline-container h3 { margin-top: 0; color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 1.4rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .timeline-container > p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.95rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }

    .timeline-item { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .timeline-disease { font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-size: 1.05rem; }
    .timeline-bar-wrapper { width: 100%; height: 12px; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.05); border-radius: 6px; position: relative; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; overflow: hidden; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .timeline-bar { position: absolute; height: 100%; border-radius: 6px; opacity: 0.8; }
    .timeline-time { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-secondary); text-align: right; font-family: var(--font-mono); }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
